{
  "texts": [
    "However, other provisions, such as those relating to unacceptable risks (\"prohibited AI practices\") in Article 5 of the AIA, venture into the realms of non-discrimination, data protection, and even criminal procedure law when it comes to safeguards against the misuse of \"real-time\" remote biometric identification systems in public spaces for law enforcement pur-poses.",
    "This article argues that the AIA marks a significant shift from reactive to proactive AI governance, which becomes particularly visible when considering the 68 definitions enshrined in Article 3 AIA.",
    "For the better or worse, many of these definitions will become crucial reference points for AI governance going forward.",
    "They have been established through a democratically legitimised legislative procedure following a multi-stakeholder consultation process, in contrast to definitions purely focusing on technological developments, or economic opportunities.",
    "However, it might not come as a surprise that in absence of a universally agreed scientific definition of AI (Collins et al., 2021, p. 2), and with many of the subdomains of the field such as ML constantly evolving, it remains a complex task to create a useful legal definition of the regulatory subject (Hildebrandt, 2023)."
  ]
}